WEBVTT

00:03.340 --> 00:06.480
And so he was easily aggravated. And so a student 
says, Doc, Dr. Lindsay, should we drive our cars or

00:07.690 --> 00:14.550
some detail? Doc said, that's a detail. Then 
another one shows up his hand, and he says, ask him a

00:19.070 --> 00:25.410
similar type question. I told you that's a detail. 
And that went on, and then he just went. After a

00:30.660 --> 00:33.540
while, he just turned around and took off. And I 
said, what happened? The students asked me, what

00:35.780 --> 00:37.980
happened to him? But he was, I remember that real 
clearly. Did any student ever try to play a joke or a

00:44.040 --> 00:48.240
prank on you as a teacher? I don't know that they 
did.

00:54.300 --> 00:59.320
I think one time we may have left somebody in the 
classroom asleep, you know, after class or

00:59.400 --> 01:01.021
something like that. Did any student ever try to 
bribe you for a grade or anything like that? No. No.

01:08.100 --> 01:10.880
A lot of them coming around trying to get grades 
raised. That's a common occurrence. How would

01:12.180 --> 01:12.662
they? I'll tell you one of the things that you might 
enjoy was when we first let girls in. Old Dick

01:18.280 --> 01:22.720
Davidson over there was counseling one of them, 
and I happened to walk by the door. And the old girl

01:24.010 --> 01:26.310
was just sitting there just boo-hooing. And Dr. 
Davidson looked over and said, here comes Dr.

01:27.150 --> 01:30.790
Holland. He'll help you. He was ready to unload 
that girl. Did you ever have a parent or any other

01:36.450 --> 01:44.290
outsider try to twist your arm on anything? Yeah, I 
had one student, but he got over it. He thought his

01:46.870 --> 01:51.910
little brother was sharper than he was, and we 
hadn't placed him high enough or something,

01:52.710 --> 01:56.730
giving him tough enough courses, and it turned out 
he couldn't even handle what he had. The only

01:59.190 --> 02:06.320
problem I had, I had the only problem with two or 
three profs. The young ones that we hired, we hired

02:07.040 --> 02:16.900
one guy from, he

02:07.040 --> 02:16.900
had gone to Switzerland. What's the capital of 
that place? Bern. Bern, Lucerne, Geneva,

02:23.547 --> 02:29.710
Lausanne. I've forgotten which one it was right 
now. I don't think we've hit it. Anyway, it's a

02:33.750 --> 02:35.470
well-known university. And every one of them that 
we got out of there, they handled their situation.

02:39.630 --> 02:43.690
The students, just so rough, that the students 
couldn't get along with them. And the students

02:44.870 --> 02:48.030
couldn't get along with this fellow. And so we had 
to let him go. And since then, he got an appointment

02:53.180 --> 02:57.890
over there, and he makes a point to always send me a 
card. We had another boy, a young man that we got,

03:04.840 --> 03:09.940
came to us from MIT, just as sharp as he could be. And 
you could write a wonderful letter. But his, and

03:15.880 --> 03:18.960
when you talk to him, you'd think, this guy is just 
going to make an outstanding faculty member. I

03:24.580 --> 03:25.701
hired him. Well, Toby said, you know, that's the 
first guy that we've had that got into a squabble

03:30.360 --> 03:34.600
with everybody in the entire department, 
including all the mechanics downstairs, in less

03:34.740 --> 03:38.360
than one month. And we had to finally let him go, and 
I got him a job. I said, you people can handle

03:42.860 --> 03:46.240
somebody like this. I can't handle him, because 
he's just too overbearing. He needs a job where he

03:50.900 --> 03:52.840
put him over in a corner. And another one I'll tell 
you is Bacris. I had the opportunity, the first

03:56.540 --> 03:59.920
opportunity, to hire him. He came in over there to 
get me to hire him. And I had this young faculty that

04:02.960 --> 04:05.960
I had just hired. Most of them were 10 or 15 years 
younger than I was. And he came in there, and he had a

04:10.080 --> 04:13.200
list of books, that were longer than most, many 
bodies' list of papers. I said, how in the world do

04:18.680 --> 04:21.040
you do that? He said, well, I'll just kind of sketch 
out a few things, and I'll get somebody else to fill

04:24.260 --> 04:26.240
in those little details. But he was, I could just 
tell that guy was so overbearing. And I decided

04:31.080 --> 04:34.120
that I didn't care how good he was, that I had to 
think of the fact that I had nine or ten other

04:34.620 --> 04:38.260
faculty there that I wanted to develop. And if I had 
somebody like that, he would just try to

04:42.940 --> 04:46.580
intimidate them, and run all over them. And so I 
declined hiring him. I didn't care how good he was.

04:51.560 --> 04:53.820
You've got to look at this thing. Can you, are you 
big enough to hire somebody like that? If you're

04:56.960 --> 04:58.621
real big, you can handle him. But if you're no 
bigger than we were, you just can't handle

05:00.720 --> 05:03.560
somebody that, I don't care how good he is. Well, 
old Martell hired him. And I saw Martell later, and

05:05.660 --> 05:07.860
he said to me, he says, how in the world did you pass 
up that man? I said, well, I decided I couldn't. We

05:12.660 --> 05:14.221
couldn't work with him over there. So I'm not sure 
what he says now. But anyway, I missed my

05:16.620 --> 05:21.340
opportunity there. Let's see. One of the people I 
forgot to ask about, and if we, this is a note to the

05:24.460 --> 05:27.760
typist that moved this back up to where we were 
talking about other administrators. Dick

05:33.360 --> 05:34.395
Winerdy. Oh, he was really a good one. Dick, I gave 
him a departmental position as professor.

05:43.730 --> 05:46.730
Because he couldn't get anybody else to take him 
on. He wanted to teach this little course in

05:46.790 --> 05:49.230
activation analysis. So I made him a professor of 
chemical engineering. And he was over in the

05:52.850 --> 05:55.150
dean's office all the time. And so after he went 
with Calhoun, I'd forgotten, he'd jumped me about

06:03.190 --> 06:06.570
something. I wrote some letter to him that just 
really had a twist in it. And I sent a copy of it to

06:11.190 --> 06:12.950
Fred. And he called me. He called me up and he said, 
boy, that just tickled the life out of me. He said,

06:18.130 --> 06:21.430
but you know, I don't understand, Winerdy. When he 
was working for me, I just didn't have any problem

06:21.610 --> 06:24.930
with him. But he's giving me a lot of problems now. 
And he said, I can't understand that. And I said,

06:28.780 --> 06:31.980
well, what the problem is now, he used to be working 
for you. He's working for John Calhoun now. But the

06:34.900 --> 06:41.320
funny one was that when he got two different 
occasions, when he was already out. And he called

06:44.940 --> 06:47.380
me. And you can tell what's coming. He says, 
Charlie, being on the department staff of

06:50.540 --> 06:55.700
chemical engineering was one of the highest 
honors that I've ever had. I said, my boy wants to

06:59.970 --> 07:01.890
get into graduate school. Could you help me?

07:05.990 --> 07:12.030
And then another one was whenever he finally got 
Crosswise over there and he was looking for a home,

07:12.010 --> 07:14.510
I thought we were going to get him back. Because, 
see, he's on my faculty. And that's when the... And

07:17.330 --> 07:20.550
so he was calling up wanting to come back. That's 
right, when Dr. Miller became president. Yeah.

07:24.233 --> 07:24.911
Because... He'd been Crosswise with some of 
those. And, see, Dick and I had offices that

07:27.570 --> 07:31.250
adjoined each other. And the first three days that 
Dr. Miller was president, he didn't even say good

07:34.570 --> 07:36.590
morning to Dick. He literally did not say a word to 
him. Dick came into my office and said to me,

07:39.370 --> 07:41.970
tersely, he said, I've got to find some work 
somewhere. Well, he called me. And I told him,

07:46.610 --> 07:49.270
well, you know, we'll try to use you. Come on over, 
because I knew we were obligated to. Now, when he

07:52.610 --> 07:58.590
was working for Dean Benson, what was his task?

08:01.310 --> 08:03.890
When he was still in engineering, what was his 
task? Well, I think he had him doing... Fred put

08:06.270 --> 08:09.010
more stock in what he told him than I would have. He 
kind of had Fred buffaloed a little bit. Fred would

08:12.370 --> 08:14.870
kind of fall for some of that. Was he to try to bring 
in... Was he to try to bring in research money?

08:19.230 --> 08:23.470
Well, he was involved in a lot of the... It was more 
in research than anything else. But he got stuck on

08:27.940 --> 08:30.460
him and Newell both. And I could tell Newell was no 
good the day that he came in when he was looking for a

08:33.520 --> 08:35.300
job. And I made a couple suggestions to him, and he 
just brushed them off. And I could tell that he

08:39.240 --> 08:43.620
wasn't going to make it. But Fred did... I went 
along with him quite a while, and he was subject to

08:50.640 --> 08:54.880
being sucked in a little bit. Now, Wayne Erdy had 
that activation analysis. He didn't have it down

08:58.480 --> 09:00.600
where he could... I've forgotten. Paul Crawford 
used to laugh about it. He was looking... He had his

09:06.060 --> 09:09.680
system fixed so he could shove these samples kind 
of like J.C. Penney's all over the place, but he

09:12.700 --> 09:17.600
couldn't handle it, couldn't find silicon in 
carborundum, which is made out of... He

09:19.340 --> 09:23.670
got in the cart before the horse. Back to Joey's 
pleasures of being the department head. What are

09:31.370 --> 09:34.610
some other achievements that you remember during 
those years that you're proud to look back on? You

09:38.450 --> 09:40.550
said teaching was the biggest. Well, I got a lot of 
books published. I got seven books published, and

09:44.910 --> 09:47.930
I got a lot of them in distillation, kinetics, 
catalysis. In 93, I wrote one on quantitative

09:48.630 --> 09:50.750
cancer, modeling, and risk assessment with 
Silken, who's a statistician. And so I enjoy very

09:55.150 --> 10:02.850
much the development of ideas on paper. And, see, 
when I became department head, I realized that I

10:06.290 --> 10:09.830
didn't have time to be down in that lab working all 
the time. I just couldn't do it. And so what I did do

10:11.690 --> 10:15.170
was get into this other field, and I got started 
with Exxon down there in 1955 because I had, from a

10:18.890 --> 10:20.710
master's... a master's degree, had worked on, 
with Phil Murdoch, on algebraic solution of very

10:23.630 --> 10:28.270
simple distillation problems. And it was just 
three or four components. And I got down there, and

10:30.990 --> 10:32.960
O.B. Franklin said, well, since you're an expert 
on distillation, we're going to let you work out

10:35.930 --> 10:41.810
this big old tower, pipe still. And it had about 30 
or 40 plates and probably 500 components and

10:46.250 --> 10:48.970
streams going off everywhere. And actually, in 
the wintertime, the way we were looking at them,

10:50.870 --> 10:53.170
when you're doing finite differences, every time 
you come to a terminal condition, you've got

10:55.350 --> 10:56.891
another set of boundary conditions. I would 
have... And so they gave me that problem. And I just

10:59.990 --> 11:02.050
walked around for about two weeks trying to figure 
out how in the world... I can't even solve that

11:04.750 --> 11:06.291
little one. How in the world can I solve anything 
like this? So I finally found out a way to do it, and

11:11.190 --> 11:13.510
that's what got me started on all this other stuff. 
And they eventually were the first ones to develop

11:13.950 --> 11:17.270
a program on it, which we call the Theta Method. And 
it is still a real good... method, and it has some

11:20.890 --> 11:23.070
theoretical basis. And then I wrote a book on 
kinetics, and it's still being used over there.

11:33.350 --> 11:34.731
The one on kinetics is used, and also we're using 
the one on distillation. So those two books are

11:38.510 --> 11:41.650
still in use. What were your guidelines for being a 
good department head?

11:50.560 --> 11:51.301
Oh, I don't know. I just tried to treat everybody 
fair. That was all. It just kind of... I'm going to

11:55.380 --> 11:57.720
treat them like you'd like to be treated yourself, 
as near as you can. And it's hard to do that, but to

12:00.820 --> 12:03.080
not have any... be favoritism over one or the 
other, try to have an open door to any of them that

12:11.490 --> 12:13.031
had any problem, and have some concern. It's very 
difficult, but that's what I tried to do, and tried

12:23.140 --> 12:26.220
to help them as much as I could with what helped them 
advance their own careers. And

12:29.380 --> 12:35.400
you obviously had some graduate students. Which 
are the graduate students you're most proud to

12:36.280 --> 12:40.680
claim? Oh,

12:42.730 --> 12:46.990
let's see. There were several of them that had done 
real well. Norman Tetlow was one of them who went to

12:51.590 --> 12:53.750
Dow that developed a whole design package for 
them. And Ron McDaniel was also with him down

12:57.940 --> 13:01.560
there. And... And... Then Narker, I don't know, he 
was a graduate student, worked over at the Center

13:07.270 --> 13:09.550
some, was another good one. I've had a lot of good 
graduate students. And so... And some of them

13:14.810 --> 13:22.030
very, very good. In fact, I had two, Dan Taylor and 
Park Davis, that both went to Rice. And I got them as

13:27.510 --> 13:29.350
graduate students. And they also worked with... 
took some courses under Dr. Kleppel. He said that

13:33.430 --> 13:34.451
they were... two of the best mathematical minds 
that he had seen come through from engineering.

13:40.940 --> 13:46.960
That they just, they could handle it, and they were 
good students. With what other institutions did

13:46.940 --> 13:50.580
you most closely cooperate? Oh, I did some with the 
University of Texas, but not anything in real

13:50.560 --> 13:56.920
detail. But Ben Winkle over there was, he worked in 
distillation, but he did more of the experimental

14:03.080 --> 14:11.160
homework, and I was, I'd gotten off into the other 
design, it's really design methods. I'd gotten

14:11.140 --> 14:17.640
into that because that's all a department head's 
got time to do, and also with Bill Akers down at

14:17.620 --> 14:25.280
Rice, you may have known of him, he was, he went to 
Tech and later went on and got his degrees at Rice

14:25.260 --> 14:29.040
and stayed down there with the administration for 
a good long while. As the enrollment at A&M began to

14:31.120 --> 14:33.300
change. Yeah. Women were admitted, CORE became 
volunteer, and so forth, did that, how did that

14:34.246 --> 14:39.480
affect the department? I, the only thing that 
affected us was whenever the enrollment got away,

14:42.050 --> 14:49.840
and we just were looking at the possibility of 
having to run labs night and day, and all that kind

14:49.820 --> 14:54.040
of thing. That was the only thing, and that kind of 
came to an end, and we didn't have the space for it.

15:01.318 --> 15:04.340
But other than that, I'd say that over the years, 
that the staff, the students, they have really

15:04.320 --> 15:07.500
gotten better. I've got a real excellent class 
right now.

15:13.840 --> 15:18.780
I remember when I first started teaching, there 
was a tendency for students to think, well, by the

15:18.760 --> 15:23.340
time we get to be seniors, we've already got the 
fundamental knowledge. All we're going to do from

15:23.320 --> 15:27.390
here on is think, and solve problems. But they 
didn't have it all, and they didn't, um, if you gave

15:27.370 --> 15:35.530
them something new, they'd They'd say, well, we 
haven't had that, you know, as if that weren't fair

15:35.510 --> 15:39.790
territory. But the students now just take it. 
Anything comes at them. Do you think that the

15:44.070 --> 15:49.510
courses that you and your colleagues teach now are 
more demanding? Oh, yeah, they are. And they're

15:52.250 --> 15:53.970
higher quality. Actually, I was disappointed 
when I got my degree in chemical engineering

15:59.250 --> 16:03.270
because I'd had a pretty good background in 
mathematics and science, and they weren't using

16:03.290 --> 16:04.111
it. They were just using mainly arithmetic. And 
they made it hard but just giving you catchy

16:06.650 --> 16:10.650
problems. That's why they kept the grades down. 
But the material they really covered wasn't

16:13.750 --> 16:17.750
really all that hard, the fundamentals. Another 
thing we had was open book, which encouraged you

16:18.770 --> 16:22.770
not to do anything, which is not near as good as 
thinking that you're going to have to go in there

16:28.840 --> 16:32.240
and have it all in your mind so that you can spend 
your time working the problems through the thumb

16:32.220 --> 16:33.421
and through the book. And when you give open book 
quizzes, what happens is that you give something

16:35.960 --> 16:39.080
they can't find in there anyway. And so I think it's 
better. After that, I never did give open book

16:42.320 --> 16:44.620
quizzes. I just felt like that you can, students 
will do better if they have to. There's certain

16:50.620 --> 16:53.540
tools that you're going to have to learn 
regardless. And just well learn them. It may be

16:55.660 --> 17:01.100
drudgery, but there's certain, a carpenter's got 
to have a hammer and a saw, and if you're going to do

17:01.080 --> 17:02.980
any good, you need something. There's certain 
fundamentals that you understand thoroughly,

17:05.740 --> 17:07.001
and you don't have to be looking them up. As women 
began to be in the classroom, did you all have any

17:13.100 --> 17:17.660
examples of where somebody forgot that he was 
speaking now to a mixed audience and said

17:17.640 --> 17:21.840
something? I don't know, but I got one of these 
reports back once, and I could never figure out

17:24.640 --> 17:28.020
what I had done that was sexy or something. And it 
baffled me. I've never been called on it but once,

17:31.120 --> 17:33.480
but I don't know. What it was, it must have been 
somebody gave a poor grade because I've never been

17:36.000 --> 17:38.720
called on it before, and I never tell anything in 
class that's off color. The only thing that I did

17:43.150 --> 17:52.740
tell, I

17:43.150 --> 17:52.740
did show them a film that I had, some slides that I 
had made, and that might have been, that's the only

17:56.850 --> 17:58.011
thing I could figure. I was teaching a course on 
quantitative cancer modeling and risk

17:57.990 --> 18:04.650
assessment, and going back, and I knew it was on, 
and I was given a little bit on waste disposal. The

18:09.460 --> 18:15.640
first garbage disposal place was right outside of 
Jerusalem. And it's the Greek name now that's for

18:16.970 --> 18:21.820
hell. It means the same thing. It was a mess. And I 
was, that was one of the things I pointed out. But

18:28.940 --> 18:33.760
before I did that, I went back and pointed out that 
probably,

18:36.760 --> 18:45.090
hazardous waste incineration, or incineration 
began about 500,000 years ago. And what I had was, I

18:45.070 --> 18:49.510
got somebody to draw me this cartoon and it showed 
these women were logging, were lugging the wood

18:49.490 --> 18:54.770
on, throwing it on the fire and the men were all 
sitting back watching them. And I said, boy, in

18:55.750 --> 18:59.070
those days, men had it made. And that's the only 
thing that I can figure out that I might have said

18:59.050 --> 19:06.330
that I never did know what it was. But in general, 
I'll tell you, the girls, what'll happen is only

19:07.070 --> 19:13.920
the good ones will stay in. The poor ones that see 
they can't make it, they're not like the boys. The

19:18.780 --> 19:22.580
poor ones will drop out and go take another major. 
You got some boys that'll stay in there until the

19:22.560 --> 19:26.280
bitter end. And that's the difference you see. 
Usually the girls are near the top of the class. As

19:32.910 --> 19:37.790
far as you and your colleagues knew, was chemical 
engineering one of the most demanding majors on

19:37.790 --> 19:41.750
the campus, in terms of power? Well, I think 
electrical was real demanding. I think chemical

19:44.410 --> 19:47.010
and electrical. And mechanical was fairly 
demanding. Those three were pretty demanding.

19:50.430 --> 19:53.370
I'd say electrical maybe. Electrical and 
chemical were probably two of the most demanding.

19:57.620 --> 20:02.360
And I don't know, I imagine it would depend on your 
aptitude as to which you would think would be the

20:02.340 --> 20:03.961
most demanding. That reminds me to go way back to 
the 80s. I think it was the 80s. I think it was the

20:06.670 --> 20:07.691
80s. I think it was the early 60s again, as you and I 
and others were part of that committee

20:13.190 --> 20:17.650
recommending the new name for this institution. 
Did you and your colleagues in engineering have a

20:17.630 --> 20:22.090
preference for what the name ought to be or ought 
not to be? You know, I haven't thought about it

20:23.810 --> 20:27.510
since then. No, I don't really. I don't know that at 
that time that we would have gone with Texas A&M

20:30.190 --> 20:36.920
University, though. I understand. I understand. 
Yeah. I understand that. I understand that. And

20:42.020 --> 20:43.795
then the president over there, then Vice 
President Hall, he said that Mr. Rudder could not

20:44.040 --> 20:49.380
at all accept losing the A&M. And our committee, 
remember, recommended Texas State University.

20:52.500 --> 20:52.847
Yeah. Because everybody else was going that way. 
Right. And he said, Mr. Rudder just didn't like

20:55.475 --> 20:57.120
that at all. And Dr. Hall said, he's the one that 
came up with what it now is, the A&M with no periods

21:02.860 --> 21:04.680
and so forth. Mm-hm. And as I look back, okay. 
Everybody knows what. school it is yeah and it's a

21:07.940 --> 21:13.540
no it doesn't mean that anymore no that's right and 
so i think it was a good deal going that that's what

